  "success": true,
  "output": "## Findings\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraping pipeline (no React/frontend exists â€” `agent.py`, `fetchers.py`, `store.py`, `pipeline.py`), so I've mapped the requested categories onto their actual analogues here. With 132 sources configured (`sources.yaml`), several of these scale badly.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern â€” `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nEvery job fetched does its own `SELECT` in a Python loop, then its own `INSERT`/`UPDATE`. With 132 sources and boards like Apple (~6,400 roles) or Amazon/Microsoft (thousands), this is potentially tens of thousands of round-trips to SQLite per run.\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    ...\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()  # N+1\n```\n\n**Fix**: bulk-load existing hashes once, then diff in memory:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's ~999 var limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i+900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?'*len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update(cur.execute(q, chunk).fetchall())  # or dict((r[\"key\"], r[\"content_hash\"]) for r in ...)\n\n    new, changed, seen_same = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); self._update(cur, job, now)\n        else:\n            seen_same.append(job.key)\n    if seen_same:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", [(now, k) for k in seen_same])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) queries into O(N/900) + 2 bulk writes.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation â€” regex recompiled per job â€” `filters.py:11-27`\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(exclude)`/`_compile(include)` **inside itself** â€” so the same include/exclude keyword lists get re-compiled into regex objects for every single job in the run, even though the rules never change within a call.\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), exclude=..., ...)]\n    # match() -> _compile(exclude) / _compile(include) EVERY call\n```\n\n**Fix**: compile once, pass the compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=(), exclude=(), locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude): return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include): return False\n    ...\n```\n\nFor thousands of jobs Ă— several keywords each, this eliminates thousands of unnecessary `re.compile` calls per run.\n\n### 3. Redundant computation â€” `Job.key`/`Job.content_hash` recomputed & `to_row()` deep-copies `raw` â€” `models.py:55-75`\n\n`key` and `content_hash` are plain `@property`, not cached, and `content_hash` does a SHA-256 hash each access. In `store.diff()`, `job.key` is accessed in the `SELECT`, then `to_row()` (called from `_insert`/`_update`) recomputes both `key` *and* `content_hash` again â€” plus `to_row()` calls `dataclasses.asdict(self)`, which **deep-copies every field including `raw`** before immediately popping it:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)      # deep-copies raw (the full API payload) for nothing\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)    # ...then throws it away\n```\n\n**Fix**: build the row dict manually instead of `asdict`, and compute `key`/`content_hash` once:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    return {\n        \"key\": self.key, \"source\": self.source, \"company\": self.company,\n        \"external_id\": self.external_id, \"title\": self.title, \"url\": self.url,\n        \"location\": self.location, \"department\": self.department,\n        \"employment_type\": self.employment_type, \"posted_at\": self.posted_at,\n        \"salary_range\": self.salary_range, \"content_hash\": self.content_hash,\n    }\n```\n\nThis also fixes the `raw`-deep-copy cost, which leads to the next finding.\n\n### 4. Memory bloat â€” `Job.raw` is populated everywhere but never read â€” `fetchers.py` (all `parse_*` functions)\n\nI grepped the whole repo for `.raw` usage: it's **written** in nearly every parser (`raw=j`, sometimes the full unfiltered API record) but **never read** anywhere downstream â€” `to_row()` immediately discards it, and nothing else touches `Job.raw`. For big boards (Apple's `results` list, Greenhouse's full job dict, etc.) this means the pipeline holds thousands of redundant full JSON payloads in memory simultaneously for no benefit.\n\n**Fix**: stop populating `raw` by default, or gate it behind a debug flag:\n\n```python\n# models.py\nDEBUG_RAW = os.getenv(\"JOBSQUARE_DEBUG_RAW\") == \"1\"\n\n# fetchers.py, e.g. parse_greenhouse\nout.append(Job(..., raw=j if DEBUG_RAW else {}))\n```\n\nOr simply delete the `raw=j` / `raw={...}` kwargs from all parsers if nothing external needs it â€” cheapest fix, removes both the memory overhead and the `asdict` deep-copy cost in one move.\n\n### 5. Caching opportunity â€” no conditional HTTP requests for boards hit every run\n\nPer the commit history this runs on a 12h schedule, hitting the same 132 endpoints repeatedly (`fetchers.py`). None of the fetchers send `If-None-Match`/`If-Modified-Since`, so every run re-downloads and re-parses full boards (Apple ~6,400 roles across ~10 pages, Amazon/Microsoft thousands) even when nothing changed.\n\n**Fix**: for platforms that return `ETag`/`Last-Modified` (worth checking Greenhouse/Lever/Ashby specifically â€” many do), store the last header value in the `meta` table (already used for `last_scan`/`report_seq`) keyed by source, and send it back:\n\n```python\netag = store.get_meta(f\"etag:{ats}:{company}\")\nheaders = {\"If-None-Match\": etag} if etag else {}\nr = await client.get(url, headers=headers)\nif r.status_code == 304:\n    return []  # unchanged, skip parsing entirely\nstore.set_meta(f\"etag:{ats}:{company}\", r.headers.get(\"ETag\", \"\"))\n```\n\nEven without conditional requests, this would cut parse/CPU work on unchanged boards to near zero.\n\n### 6. Minor â€” sequential blocking notifier calls â€” `notify.py:105-109`\n\n`dispatch()` runs `notify_console/slack/webhook/email/sms` sequentially, and several use blocking `httpx.post`/`smtplib` inside a function called from `pipeline.py` (itself async but calling `dispatch` synchronously post-await â€” not blocking the event loop, so this is low severity, just wasted wall-clock if multiple notifiers are configured). If more notifiers get added, worth switching to `httpx.AsyncClient` + `asyncio.gather` so a slow SMTP/Twilio call doesn't serialize behind Slack.\n\n---\n\n**No React/frontend code exists in this repo** â€” `output/`, `templates/`, `reports/` appear to be generated HTML/PDF artifacts (per `agent.py`'s `pdf-render` command), not a client-rendered UI, so \"unnecessary re-renders\" doesn't apply here.\n\n**Priority**: #1 (N+1 in `store.diff`) is the highest-impact fix given 132 sources and boards with thousands of listings â€” it turns an O(N) round-trip cost into O(N/900). #2 and #3 are cheap, safe wins. #4 (`raw` field) is worth confirming nothing external (e.g. a debugging mode) relies on it before deleting.\n",
